description: This Christmas event is held every year from December 1st to 25th in Hakodate, Hokkaido. The magnificent Christmas tree put up and decorated by the sea in front of the Kanemori Red Brick Storehouse is a gift sent from Hakodate's sister city Halifax, Canada. Every evening at 6pm, a tree lighting is performed by individuals including everyday citizens, business leaders, or even the Japan Coast Guard mascot. The tree lights and fireworks simultaneously color the sea and night sky in Hakodate. Concerts and illumination contests are held throughout the festival.

description: Held in Hakodate Port, an important transport hub connecting Hokkaido and Honshu with an excellent natural harbor, the Hakodate Port Fireworks is a dynamic fireworks show that makes the most of the location. From the 600-meter venue stretching along the waterfront from Toyokawa Pier to the Mashumaru Aomori-Hakodate Ferry Commemorative Museum, visitors can enjoy the art of astounding creative fireworks launched from up to five locations as they paint Hakodate's night sky with light and sound, including starmines, fireworks placed on the surface of the bay, and digitally linked wide-area star mines.

description: A thriving port town since the Edo period, Hakodate was frequently struck by major fires. The great fire of March 1934 was especially widespread, claiming more than 2,000 lives, and the Hakodate Minato Matsuri was held as way to help the city recover from this blow. There are many events scheduled, including a beer garden, live concerts, and a public exhibition by the Maritime Self Defense Force, as well as the exciting "Wasshoi Hakodate" parade, in which citizens sing and perform traditional dances such as the Aomori Nebuta festival dance, minato odori (port dance), and ika odori (squid dance). This is the main portion of the festival, along with a huge fireworks display that lights up the night sky.
